edge they needed to change urban conditions. This information, Fronc demonstrates, eventually empowered government regulators in the Progressive era and beyond, strengthening a federal state that grew increasingly repressive in the interest of pursuing a national security agenda. Revealing the central role of undercover investigation in both social change and the constitution of political authority, New York Undercover narrates previously untold chapters in the history of vice and the emergence of the modern surveillance state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSocial actionxHistoryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial actionzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aSocial problemsxHistoryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial problemszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aUndercover operationsxHistoryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aUndercover operationszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aprogressive era, new york, united states of america, american culture, history, historical context, private surveillance, social activism, investigators, journalism, journalists, gambling, brothels, criminal gangs, political organizations, national civic federation, urban conditions, government regulators, politics, undercover, raids, informants, gender, race, racism, jim crow laws, segregation, immigrants, immigration, working class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022626609140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226266114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226266114/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 